LGPL COMPONENT — Word/OMML export
---------------------------------
  mathml2omml              LGPL-3.0-or-later

The Word (.docx) export converts MathML to OMML using `mathml2omml`, which is
licensed under LGPL-3.0-or-later. To keep Formulize's own MIT code unaffected,
this dependency is:

  * ISOLATED behind the `OmmlConverter` interface (src/core/omml.ts), and
  * DYNAMICALLY imported (never statically bundled into the core entry points),
    so it is only loaded if and when a user invokes Word export.

Because mathml2omml is used as a separate, dynamically-loaded library (not
modified and not statically linked into the MIT code), Formulize as a whole
remains distributable under MIT while `mathml2omml` remains under LGPL-3.0.
Consumers who wish to avoid LGPL entirely can:

  * inject a permissive converter via `setOmmlConverter(...)`, or
  * simply not use the Word export capability (all other formats — LaTeX,
    MathML, SVG, PNG, Unicode — are LGPL-free), or
  * rely on the guaranteed .docx text fallback, which does not require the
    converter.

If mathml2omml is unavailable at runtime, Word export degrades gracefully to a
valid .docx containing the formula as text; nothing throws.
